text: <@U4V5EHQ2G> I think this week's debate about Maze of Ith is a little contradictory. Several times you say you shouldn't count it in your land count, but then the biggest ding you give it is it doesn't tap for mana. If you don't consider it a land, that 's like dinging an enchantment that doesn't tap for mana.
Shouldn't count it as in when you're counting how many lands you need for the deck to function
As in literally shouldn't count it
I agree, so you shouldn't ding that it doesn't tap for mana because that's already taken into account in your build.
It is a downside though, becuase the advantages of utility lands are that they don't take up a slot in the deck. That's the downside with Maze in that unlike say Kor Haven it takes up a card slot

I personally was scattered on the back half this week. I do a big 5-6 page sheet of notes for shows, but I delete my answers when I send them to Chris and Max, and I didn't realize until half way through that I had overwritten my copy, so I didn't have my answers to stuff, transitions between topics, etc. written out
So yeah I should have made that point more clearly but I was winging it a bit
Gotcha.
if im playing lands like tabernacle, maze of ith, bazaar, etc. i make sure to put a urbor and chromatic lantern in there

Games: best game for me yesterday was Gonti playing against Yevva, Nekusar and Arabo. Arabo was killed by Yevva stompy, but I'd put out Necropotence with Mana Crypt and drew 20 cards, bringing my life down to 3. I made a case to the Yevva player to kill Nekusar because I wanted to die to my own Mana Crypt trigger at upkeep. Secretly I had my wincon in my hand and if I didn't, I could win. He agreed because that was fun, and I was rolling well on Crypt triggers, only loosing 2 out of like 6, so it came to my turn, I rolled and hazzah! I made it. I proceeded to play out Paradox Engine and from there exiled everyone's libraries. At the end I was at 2 life.

I think I said this too but the biggest problem with Maze is that the things you most want to remove from combat are almost always wearing Greaves, etc. That doesn't make it still not good, but it's hard to rely upon

How many can be under a given sprocket?
You have a separate contraption deck. It's 15 card singleton in constructed. To assemble one or more contraptions, you draw from your contraption deck and put those cards on a sprocket.
The creatures will probably have abilities. “Whenever I deal damage to a player, assemble a contraption”
Any number of contraptions can be on any given sprocket.

No cuz the sprocket card says there can be multiple under any sprocket. So you can put a little under each sprocket so you get a small effect each turn, or a whole bunch under one sprocket so you get a huge payoff every three turns
Each turn your Crank! counter moves to the next sprocket. When it does you can crank any number of contraptions on that sprocket.
